    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nAfter this commit https://github.com/neovim/neovim/commit/96128a5076b7e45fc01163151401a9e2acdff565 the behavior of `NVIM_APPNAME` seems to have changed. Since, I'm using Neovim nightly images, I can't be certain 100% of whether this specific commit is responsible or something else. It's just that looking through the commits in between the 2 nightly images, this specific commit made more sense regarding the error that I got. \r\n\r\n`:h $NVIM_APPNAME` mentions the following\r\n> `$NVIM_APPNAME` must be a name, such as \"foo\", or a relative path, such as \"foo/bar\".\r\n\r\nI'm used to just having a directory `~/.config/test_configs/` in which I create different directories for different distros or other users' Neovim configurations I would like to test. \r\n\r\nAfter the change in the commit mentioned above, I get an error \r\n```\r\nnvim: Failed to --listen: \"no such file or directory\"\r\n                                                     More info with \"nvim -h\"\r\n```\r\nwhen trying to do `NVIM_APPNAME=test_configs/test nvim` for example.\r\n\r\nOn another note this does not seem to happen when you just create a directory `~/.config/test/` and clone there whatever you want and then you run `NVIM_APPNAME=test nvim`. It seems to throwing the error on relative paths from what I tested.\r\n\r\nPS: Neovim stable 0.10.1 works as expected. And if I rollback to a version before this commit, then Neovim nightly also works correctly.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. Create directory `~/.config/test_configs/test/`.\r\n2. `git clone https://github.com/LazyVim/starter ~/.config/test_configs/test` (just an example distro, I've also tried AstroNvim with same result)\r\n3. NVIM_APPNAME=test_configs/test nvim and observe what happens\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\n`$NVIM_APPNAME` should behave as before the change in commit https://github.com/neovim/neovim/commit/96128a5076b7e45fc01163151401a9e2acdff565. \r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.11.0-dev-705+gae9674704\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nNot tested\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nLinux Mint 21.3\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkitty 0.36.1\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-kitty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nI used [bob](https://github.com/MordechaiHadad/bob) to install Neovim",
